708971f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 52nd Street
708971f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, north from 52nd Street, showing prominently St. Thomas' P. E. Church (N. W. corner of 53rd Street) and the Fifth Avenue Presbyterian Church (N. W. corner of 55th Street). Between these is St. Lukes Hospital and its wooded grounds. Note the vacant space on the left, same being the 52nd to 53rd Street frontage. The Wm. K. Vanderbilt chateau and several brownstones were later built there. Incidently, St Thomas' was erected in 1870 and the Fifth Avenue Presbyterian Church, in 1875.
1876
W. S. Roege, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection
REPRODUCTION RICHTS UNENOWN

708967f.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 52nd Street (East)
708967f.text:
Fifth Ave., east side, north from East 52nd to 53rd Streets, showing the "Osborne" at No. 667. On the right appears the north side of East 52nd Street, east to Madison Ave. and containing the coach stables of individuals who resided on the avenues. The 4-story corner building No. 659 in conjunction with the Osborne became prior to 1885 the Langham Hotel. These numbers given are of the respective periods involved; there being
a variance in Atlases.
About 1879.

708947f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 52nd Street
708947f-a.text: Fifth Avenue, north across bSnd Street, showing an early view of this important Manhattan thoroughfare. Prominently shown are the two churches long identified with this locale. Respectively they are, St. Thomas' P. E. Church, erebted in 1870 at the N. W. corner of 53rd Street, and the Fifth Avenue Presbyterian Church, erected in 1875 at the N. W. corner of 55th Street. Preceding the latter are the trees in front of St. Lukes Hospital. Beyond is Central Park and its"Gold Coast". The Vm. E. Vanderbilt chateau-like mansion is on the left, at the N. W. corner of 52nd Street. Partially appearing on the margin ia the home of Mrs. Elliot F. Shepard.

First St. Thomas (Protestant Episcopal) edifice is at right centre:this was burned ahd was later rebuilt.

708966f-b.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 52nd Street (West)
708966f-b.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, from West 52nd (left), to 53rd (right) Streets, viewed )i0rthwestward from the S. E. corner of the Avenue and East 52nd Street. View No. 2 shows solely the six story office structure, No. 670 Fifth Avenue, and is
photographed from the N. E. corner of 53rd Street.
Under demolition in View 1 is the six story residence of William E. Vanderbilt Jr. An eleven story building was erected
here, continuing the old number, 666 Fifth Avenue.
To the left are two buildings that together replaced the palatial, former residence of Wm. K. Vanderbilt Sr. This stood
at the N. W. corner of 52nd Street.
To the right is the aforementioned No. 67O Fifth Avenue. Prior to 1904, this site was equally divided between the four story homes of Almy G. Gallatin (No. 670) and E. F. Coe (No. 668). Note there, the partial glimpse of the corner tower of St. Thomas P. E. Church. This edifice is at the N. W. corner
of Fifth Avenue and West 53rd Street.
